NEXUS: "The cascade failure may have disrupted routing paths across the station.
       When packets travel from source to destination, they pass through routers
       and gateways. traceroute and mtr reveal this path - showing every hop
       and identifying where latency or failures occur."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
traceroute shows the path packets take through the network. Each "hop" is a
router or gateway between you and the destination. In our Docker environment,
paths are short, but these tools are essential for real-world debugging.

mtr (My Traceroute) combines ping and traceroute for continuous monitoring,
showing packet loss and latency statistics at each hop.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Basic Traceroute
    Command: traceroute server
    See the path to the server (likely 1 hop on Docker network).

[ ] Task 2: Traceroute to External Host
    Command: traceroute -m 10 8.8.8.8
    See the path through Docker to the internet. (-m 10 limits hops)

[ ] Task 3: Different Traceroute Methods
    Command: traceroute server          # UDP (default)
    Command: traceroute -I server       # ICMP (like ping)
    Command: traceroute -T -p 80 server # TCP (useful when ICMP blocked)

[ ] Task 4: Use mtr for Continuous Monitoring
    Command: mtr server
    Press 'q' to quit. Note the Loss%, Avg, Best, and Worst columns.

[ ] Task 5: mtr Report Mode
    Command: mtr -r -c 10 server
    Generate a quick report (-r) with 10 packets (-c 10).

[ ] Task 6: Check Your Routing Table
    Command: ip route
    Command: ip route get 172.20.0.20
    Command: ip route get 172.21.0.40
    Understand what routes exist and why some destinations are unreachable.

[ ] Task 7: Trace to Unreachable Network
    Command: traceroute 172.21.0.40
    See what happens when there's no route to the destination.

[ ] Task 8: Path Analysis Checklist
    Run these commands to fully understand your routing:

    ip addr show eth0          # Your IP
    ip route                   # All routes
    ip route get 172.20.0.20   # Route to frontend
    ip route get 172.21.0.40   # Route to backend (fails)
    ip neigh                   # ARP table (Layer 2)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

KEY CONCEPTS
════════════
  traceroute    Show path to destination
  -m N          Max hops
  -I            Use ICMP instead of UDP
  -T            Use TCP instead of UDP
  -p PORT       Specify port (with -T)

  mtr           Continuous path monitoring
  -r            Report mode (non-interactive)
  -c N          Send N packets

OUTPUT COLUMNS (mtr):
  Loss%    Packet loss at this hop
  Snt      Packets sent
  Last     Last RTT
  Avg      Average RTT
  Best     Best (lowest) RTT
  Wrst     Worst (highest) RTT

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Create a file called 'path_report.txt' with:
  Line 1: How many hops to reach 'server'? (a number, likely 1)
  Line 2: Is there a route to 172.21.0.0/24 in your routing table? (yes or no)

Run: ./verify

Success: You can trace network paths, use mtr for monitoring, and understand
routing table output.

